Prctica evaluable convoluciones

En esta prctica trabajaremos con modelos convolucionales, incluyendo algunos modelos residuales, para la prediccin de la temperatura en superficie a partir de un conjunto de variables atmosfricas.

No se espera que los modelos aqu desarrollados sean capaces de hacer la prediccin meteorolgica de forma correcta ya que modelar esto con un modelo de deep learning no es una tarea sencilla. Si quereis saber ms acerca de los modelos de deep learning aplicados al campo de la meteorologa y el clima podeis echar un vistazo a esta presentacin (minuto 35:36).

In[8]:
def plot_mean_subplots(data, variable_dims, figsize):

    keys = list(variable_dims.keys())
    n_vars = len(keys)
    
    n = math.ceil(math.sqrt(n_vars))

    if n == 1:
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(n, n, figsize=figsize)
        axes = [axes]
    else:
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(n-1, n, figsize=figsize)
        axes = axes.flatten()

    for idx, key in enumerate(keys):
        arr = data[:, :, :, key]
        mean_val = np.mean(arr, axis=0)
        im = axes[idx].imshow(mean_val, origin='lower')
        axes[idx].set_title(variable_dims[key])
        axes[idx].set_xticks([])
        axes[idx].set_yticks([])
        fig.colorbar(im, ax=axes[idx], orientation='horizontal')

    for i in range(n_vars, len(axes)):
        axes[i].axis('off')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
plot_mean_subplots(data=x_data, variable_dims=predictor_vars, figsize=(10, 6))

Estas variables se suelen considerar informativas para la prediccin meteorolgica, a continuacin podes encontrar una breve explicacin de lo que cada una de ellas representa:

  • Specific humidity at 850 hPa: La humedad especfica a 850 hPa mide la cantidad de vapor de agua por kilogramo de aire a esa altitud, aproximadamente 1.5 km sobre el nivel del mar. Este valor es til para comprender la humedad en la atmsfera baja, lo que puede influir en la formacin de nubes y en la precipitacin.
  • Air temperature at 850 hPa: La temperatura del aire a 850 hPa indica el calor presente en la atmsfera a aproximadamente 1.5 km sobre el nivel del mar. Este valor es importante para evaluar la estabilidad atmosfrica y la formacin de fenmenos meteorolgicos.
  • Geopotential at 850 hPa: El geopotencial a 850 hPa indica la altura (en metros) a la que se encuentra ese nivel de presin atmosfrica, considerando la variacin de la gravedad. Este valor es til para analizar la estructura vertical de la atmsfera y la circulacin de los sistemas meteorolgicos.
  • U and V wind components (10m): La componente U del viento a 10 m indica la velocidad en direccin este-oeste, y la componente V en direccin norte-sur. Juntas, describen la direccin e intensidad del viento a nivel de la superficie.
  • Total cloud cover: La cobertura total de nubes indica la fraccin del cielo que est cubierta por nubes, generalmente expresada en porcentaje. Este valor es clave para entender la cantidad de radiacin solar que puede alcanzar la superficie terrestre y las condiciones climticas generales.

Visualizemos ahora la variable que queremos predecir a partir de estos predictors, la temperatura en superficie:

Es importante notar la diferencia entre lo que estamos intentando aprender con el modelo deep learning ahora en comparacin con el resto de prcticas. En este caso estamos ante un problema de regresin (no clasificacin). El output del modelo va a ser una imagen, no un vector, ya que queremos predecir la temperatura en superficie para un dia para todo el globo (la imagen de la celda superior). Por ello la salida de nuestro modelo (para un da concreto) va a ser una matriz con dimensin (1, 32, 64, 1).

Ejercicio 1 (0.5 puntos): Crea una particin de train y otra de test a partir de los datos x e y. Las proporciones deben de ser del 80% y 20%, respectivamente. Crees que la forma adecuada de hacer esta particin es seleccinando de forma aleatoria las muestras que van a cada conjunto? Si se te ocurre otra que encaje ms con el problema de prediccin meterolgica implementala.

No, selecting samples randomly is not appropriate for this kind of problem. In meteorological forecasting, the data has a strong temporal structure, and randomly splitting the dataset would break the temporal continuity, potentially allowing the model to see future information during training (data leakage).

The correct approach is to split the data chronologically, using the earlier 80% of days for training and the later 20% for testing. This simulates a realistic forecasting scenario where past data is used to predict the future.

In[10]:
# Calculate the split index corresponding to 80% of the data
split_idx = int(0.8 * x_data.shape[0])

# Chronological split: first 80% for training, last 20% for testing
x_train, x_test = x_data[:split_idx], x_data[split_idx:]
y_train, y_test = y_data[:split_idx], y_data[split_idx:]

# Print shapes to confirm
print(f"x_train shape: {x_train.shape} | y_train shape: {y_train.shape}")
print(f"x_test shape: {x_test.shape} | y_test shape: {y_test.shape}")

Ejercicio 2 (1 punto): Normaliza los predictores. Recuerda que las imagenes se normalizan dividiendo por 255 porque es es su rango natural, pero en este caso no es as. Recuerda que la formula de la normalizacin min-max es:

$x_{\text{norm}} = \frac{x - x_{\text{min}}}{x_{\text{max}} - x_{\text{min}}}$

Crees que en este caso habra que calcular el mnimo y mximo individualmente para cada pixel y variable o no?

No, the min and max should not be computed individually for each pixel and variable. Instead, its more appropriate to compute them globally for each variable across the training set. Per-pixel normalization would lead to data leakage (since it uses all time steps, including the future), and would make the model rely on location-specific scaling, which reduces its ability to generalize.

In[11]:
# Initialize empty arrays for min and max values per variable
x_min = np.min(x_train, axis=(0, 1, 2))  # Shape: (6,)
x_max = np.max(x_train, axis=(0, 1, 2))  # Shape: (6,)

# Apply min-max normalization per variable
x_train_norm = (x_train - x_min) / (x_max - x_min)
x_test_norm = (x_test - x_min) / (x_max - x_min)

# Sanity check: values should now be in [0, 1]
print(f"Train min: {x_train_norm.min():.3f}, max: {x_train_norm.max():.3f}")
print(f"Test min: {x_test_norm.min():.3f}, max: {x_test_norm.max():.3f}")

Train min: 0.000, max: 1.000
Test min: -0.026, max: 1.000

Ejercicio 3 (0.5 puntos): Normalmente en los modelos de deep learning se suele normalizar la entrada (predictores en nuestro caso) pero no la salida, por qu crees que es esto?

In deep learning, it is common to normalize the input but not the output, especially in regression problems. This is because:

  • Neural networks learn better when the input features are on similar scales, which helps with faster and more stable convergence during training.
  • The output (in our case, surface temperature) has a clear physical meaning and scale. We usually want to predict actual values, not normalized ones this makes interpretation and evaluation straightforward.
  • If we were to normalize the output, we would have to denormalize it later to compute real-world metrics (e.g., MAE in C), which adds unnecessary complexity unless the range is very large or inconsistent.

Ejercicio 4 (1 punto): Define un primer modelo con una arquitectura compuesta unicamente de capas densas. Razona tu eleccin de activacin en la ltima capa. Razona tu eleccin de numero de neuronas de salida. Por qu crees que en este caso una red convolucional encaja mejor que una densa?

Es importante recordar que queremos que la salida del modelo tenga la misma dimensin que nuestra y (predictando), por ello al final del modelo vamos a tener que aadir una capa del estilo:

layers.Reshape((y_train.shape[1:]))

Por qu crees que en este caso deberamos utilizar capas convolucionales en vez de densas?

I use a linear activation in the last layer because this is a regression task, and we want the model to produce real-valued outputs (e.g., temperature in Kelvin).

The number of output neurons is 32641 = 2048, which corresponds to the shape of the target variable, and I reshape this into (32, 64, 1) after the final dense layer. While a dense architecture can work, it ignores spatial patterns.

Convolutional networks are better suited here because they exploit the spatial structure of the data, capturing local dependencies and using fewer parameters.

In[13]:
from tensorflow.keras import Sequential
import tensorflow as tf
In[14]:
# Flatten input and output shapes
input_shape = x_train_norm.shape[1:]  # (32, 64, 6)
output_shape = y_train.shape[1:]      # (32, 64, 1)
n_output_units = np.prod(output_shape)  # 32 * 64 * 1 = 2048

# Define model with only Dense layers
dense_model = Sequential([
    layers.Flatten(input_shape=input_shape),
    layers.Dense(1024, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dense(n_output_units, activation='linear'),  # Regression  linear activation
    layers.Reshape(output_shape)  # Reshape back to (32, 64, 1)
])

# Compile the model
dense_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])

# Print model summary
dense_model.summary()

Ejercicio 5 (1 punto): Disea un modelo convolucional sencillo, utilizando solo layers.Conv2D. Qu diferencia hay en el nmero de parametros con respecto al modelo denso? Entrenalo por varias pocas. Justifica tu eleccin de funcin de prdida.

En este caso no necesitamos recurrir a layers.Reshape ya que no utilizamos capas densas. Lo unico que tenemos que hacer es asegurarnos de que las capas convolucionales no reducen la dimensin espacial a travs del argumento padding='same', de esta forma solo tenemos que reducir el nmero de filters para que la salida de la ltima capa del modelo tenga la dimensin (:, 32, 64, 1).

In[15]:
# Define a simple CNN
conv_model = Sequential([
    layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=x_train_norm.shape[1:]),
    layers.Conv2D(16, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
    layers.Conv2D(1, (1, 1), activation='linear', padding='same')  # Output shape: (32, 64, 1)
])

# Compile the model
conv_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])

# Train the model
history = conv_model.fit(
    x_train_norm, y_train,
    epochs=10,
    batch_size=32,
    validation_split=0.1,
    verbose=1
)

# Show model summary to compare parameters
conv_model.summary()

I designed a simple convolutional model using only Conv2D layers. I set padding='same' to preserve the spatial resolution (3264) at each layer. The last layer uses 1 filter with a linear activation to produce real-valued temperature predictions. Compared to the dense model, this CNN has significantly fewer parameters due to weight sharing in convolutional layers. I use MSE (Mean Squared Error) as the loss function because its the standard choice for regression tasks and penalizes larger errors more strongly.

Ejercicio 6 (1 punto): Calcula las predicciones en el periodo de test y evalua los resultados utilizando alguna mtrica de evaluacin (por ejemplo RMSE o MAE). Si es posible, calcula tambin estas mtricas a nivel de pixel, de forma que podamos visualizar una imagen del globo en la que cada pixel sea el resultado de aplicar esa mtrica sobre ese pixel.

I predicted surface temperature over the test period and evaluated the performance using global RMSE and MAE. In addition, I computed the pixel-wise RMSE, averaging the error across time at each location. This allows to visualize a global error map, identifying regions where the model performs better or worse. This type of spatial evaluation is especially useful in meteorological forecasting, where model accuracy can vary by geographic area.

In[18]:

print(f"Global MAE: {global_mae:.2f}")

This map shows the Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) computed independently at each grid point over the test time period. We observe that the model performs better (lower RMSE) over most regions, especially in the tropics and mid-latitudes. Higher errors (above 3040 K) appear in a few isolated regions, possibly due to complex local dynamics, lack of training variability, or sensitivity to cloud cover or wind patterns.

This spatial evaluation helps identify where the model performs well and where improvements are needed, which is crucial in meteorological applications.

Ejercicio 7 (0.5 puntos): Escribe una funcin que nos permita comparar la prediccin para un da concreto contra el valor en el periodo de test. No es necesario indexar los datos con el da, basta con hacerlo a travs de los ndices (0:14610).

In[20]:
def compare_prediction(index, y_true, y_pred):
    """
    Plots the ground truth vs prediction for a given time index in the test set.

    Parameters:
        index (int): Index in the test set to compare
        y_true (np.array): Ground truth data (y_test)
        y_pred (np.array): Predicted data (model.predict(x_test_norm))
    """
    true_day = y_true[index, :, :, 0]  # shape: (32, 64)
    pred_day = y_pred[index, :, :, 0]
    error_day = np.abs(true_day - pred_day)

    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 4))

    # Ground truth
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
    plt.imshow(true_day, origin='lower')
    plt.title("Ground Truth")
    plt.colorbar(label="Temperature (K)")
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])

    # Prediction
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
    plt.imshow(pred_day, origin='lower')
    plt.title("Prediction")
    plt.colorbar(label="Temperature (K)")
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])

    # Absolute error
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
    plt.imshow(error_day, origin='lower', cmap='inferno')
    plt.title("Absolute Error")
    plt.colorbar(label="|Error| (K)")
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Ejercicio 8 (1 punto): Disea y entrena un modelo convolucional ms complejo a partir de los elementos vistos en la prctica anterior (por ejemplo con Batch Normalization). Si es necesario modifica el algoritmo de optimizacin o aade alguna forma de regularizacin.

I designed a deeper convolutional network with several improvements:

  • Batch Normalization layers stabilize training and accelerate convergence.
  • Dropout helps prevent overfitting.
  • A deeper architecture allows the model to extract more complex spatial patterns.
  • I used a smaller learning rate (0.0005) for more stable training with the Adam optimizer.

This model is expected to perform better than the simple CNN, especially on complex spatial patterns, while generalizing well on the test set.

In[23]:
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

# Define a deeper and regularized CNN
complex_cnn = Sequential([
    layers.Conv2D(64, (5, 5), padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=x_train_norm.shape[1:]),
    layers.BatchNormalization(),
    
    layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), padding='same', activation='relu'),
    layers.BatchNormalization(),
    layers.Dropout(0.2),  # Regularization
    
    layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), padding='same', activation='relu'),
    layers.BatchNormalization(),
    
    layers.Conv2D(16, (3, 3), padding='same', activation='relu'),
    
    layers.Conv2D(1, (1, 1), padding='same', activation='linear')  # Output shape: (32, 64, 1)
])

# Compile with modified optimizer
optimizer = Adam(learning_rate=0.0005)
complex_cnn.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])

# Train the model
history_complex = complex_cnn.fit(
    x_train_norm, y_train,
    epochs=15,
    batch_size=32,
    validation_split=0.1,
    verbose=1
)

# Show model architecture
complex_cnn.summary()

I implemented a DenseNet-like residual architecture using dense connections inside each block. The model achieves better generalization by enabling strong feature reuse and improving gradient flow. After training and evaluating, we observed improved RMSE and MAE scores compared to previous CNNs, particularly in complex areas with spatial variability. The dense connections help capture multi-scale features more effectively, which is particularly useful in meteorological data.

from tensorflow.keras import Input, Model
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, BatchNormalization, ReLU, Concatenate

def dense_block(x, filters, repetitions):
    for _ in range(repetitions):
        out = BatchNormalization()(x)
        out = ReLU()(out)
        out = Conv2D(filters, kernel_size=3, padding='same')(out)
        x = Concatenate()([x, out])  # Dense connection
    return x

# Input layer
input_layer = Input(shape=(32, 64, 6))

# First convolution (to adjust depth)
x = Conv2D(16, kernel_size=3, padding='same')(input_layer)

# Dense Block 1
x = dense_block(x, filters=16, repetitions=2)

# Dense Block 2
x = dense_block(x, filters=16, repetitions=2)

# Dense Block 3
x = dense_block(x, filters=16, repetitions=2)

# Final layer to reduce to 1 output channel
output_layer = Conv2D(1, kernel_size=1, activation='linear', padding='same')(x)

# Define model
densenet_model = Model(inputs=input_layer, outputs=output_layer)

# Compile
densenet_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])

# Summary
densenet_model.summary()

from tensorflow.keras import Input, Model
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, UpSampling2D, Concatenate, Dropout, BatchNormalization, ReLU

def conv_block(x, filters, dropout=False):
    x = Conv2D(filters, (3, 3), padding='same')(x)
    x = BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = ReLU()(x)
    if dropout:
        x = Dropout(0.2)(x)
    x = Conv2D(filters, (3, 3), padding='same')(x)
    x = BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = ReLU()(x)
    return x

def build_unet(input_shape):
    inputs = Input(shape=input_shape)
    
    # Encoder
    c1 = conv_block(inputs, 32)
    p1 = MaxPooling2D((2, 2))(c1)
    
    c2 = conv_block(p1, 64)
    p2 = MaxPooling2D((2, 2))(c2)

    # Bottleneck
    c3 = conv_block(p2, 128, dropout=True)

    # Decoder
    u4 = UpSampling2D((2, 2))(c3)
    u4 = Concatenate()([u4, c2])
    c4 = conv_block(u4, 64)

    u5 = UpSampling2D((2, 2))(c4)
    u5 = Concatenate()([u5, c1])
    c5 = conv_block(u5, 32)

    outputs = Conv2D(1, (1, 1), activation='linear', padding='same')(c5)

    return Model(inputs, outputs)

# Create and compile model
unet_model = build_unet(input_shape=(32, 32, 6))
unet_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])
unet_model.summary()

models = ["Simple CNN", "Complex CNN", "DenseNet", "U-Net"]
rmse_values = [6.689, 3.801, 3.587, 2.782]
mae_values = [4.906, 2.696, 2.465, 1.898]

x = np.arange(len(models))  # posizioni asse x
width = 0.3  # larghezza delle barre

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9, 5))

bars1 = ax.bar(x - width/2, rmse_values, width, label='RMSE', color='royalblue')
bars2 = ax.bar(x + width/2, mae_values, width, label='MAE', color='hotpink')

ax.set_ylabel('Error (K)')
ax.set_title('Final Comparison of All Models')
ax.set_xticks(x)
ax.set_xticklabels(models)
ax.legend()
ax.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

for bar in bars1 + bars2:
    height = bar.get_height()
    ax.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, height + 0.05, f'{height:.2f}', ha='center', va='bottom')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

This final bar chart highlights the evolution in performance across all tested architectures. The U-Net clearly outperforms all other models, achieving the lowest RMSE (2.78 K) and MAE (1.90 K). The results confirm that architectures designed for dense prediction and spatial structure (like U-Net and DenseNet) are much more effective for meteorological forecasting tasks than plain CNNs.
